  "slug": "soutzoukakia",
  "title": "Soutzoukakia",
  "subtitle": "Greek spiced meatballs in tomato sauce",
  "excerpt": "Beef meatballs scented with cumin and cinnamon, seared until dark, then baked in a wine-rich tomato sauce. A dish from Smyrna with a flavour profile unlike anything else in the Greek repertoire.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Soutzoukakia originate from Smyrna (modern Izmir, Turkey), brought to mainland Greece by refugees in the 1920s population exchange. Documented in Diane Kochilas, The Glorious Foods of Greece (2001). The cumin and cinnamon distinguish them from standard Greek keftedes.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soutzoukakia are elongated meatballs, shaped like small logs rather than balls, and they carry a combination of spices (cumin, cinnamon, garlic, red wine) that sets them apart from every other Greek dish on the table. The flavour is deep and warm, the sauce sweet-sharp from the tomato and wine.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Chilling the mixture for 30 minutes makes it easier to shape and holds the meatballs together during searing. Don't skip the sear: the Maillard crust that forms on the outside of each meatball is part of the flavour. They finish in the oven submerged in sauce, which they absorb slowly.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
