      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make and chill the mixture",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine the mince, garlic, cumin, cinnamon, wine, soaked breadcrumbs, egg, salt, and pepper. Mix thoroughly with your hands until everything is evenly distributed. Cover and refrigerate for 30 minutes. This chilling step firms the mixture and makes shaping easier.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Shape and sear",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 180°C fan. With damp hands, shape the mixture into 16 elongated meatballs, about the size and shape of a thick finger. Heat the olive oil in a large frying pan over medium-high heat. Sear the meatballs in batches until deeply browned on all sides, about 3 to 4 minutes per batch. Transfer to a baking dish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "In the same pan, cook the garlic for 1 minute, add the tomato purée and stir for another minute. Add the tinned tomatoes, wine, cinnamon, sugar, and salt. Simmer for 5 minutes. Pour the sauce over the meatballs in the baking dish. Bake for 25 minutes until the sauce has thickened and the meatballs are cooked through. Serve with rice, orzo, or crusty bread.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Chill the mixture for at least 30 minutes; handle gently and use damp hands to shape",
              "cause": "Mixture not chilled, or not enough binding",
              "symptom": "Meatballs fall apart during searing"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce to 1 tsp and increase the cinnamon slightly for a warmer, less sharp flavour",
              "cause": "Cumin can be assertive; the amount here is traditional",
              "symptom": "Cumin flavour is too dominant"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Simmer the sauce for 10 minutes before pouring over the meatballs; it will thicken further in the oven",
              "cause": "Not enough simmering time before baking",
              "symptom": "Sauce is too thin"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soutzoukakia arrived in Greece with the Asia Minor refugees of 1922 and became absorbed into the Greek kitchen as thoroughly as any dish native to the mainland. The spice profile (cumin, cinnamon, wine) speaks of Smyrna and the Ottoman kitchen. Today they are cooked in homes and tavernas across the country, though their origins are rarely mentioned.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
